{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "regulation service participation requirements",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "CAISO",
      "data_type": "report",
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "a2144460-00e9-4f8f-80fa-0c9f7a7259c8",
        "score": 0.41248694,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2022, and it discusses quarterly average day-ahead ancillary service requirements. \n\n- **Figure 5.3**: Displays the average requirements for four types of services: regulation down, regulation up, spin, and non-spin from 2019 to 2021. \n\n- **Regulation Requirements**: The California ISO calculates these based on observed needs from the previous year, updating them regularly. Adjustments can be made for higher net load variability.\n\n- **2021 Observations**: \n  - Both regulation up and down requirements decreased, but regulation down saw a significant increase, averaging 684 MW (30% increase from 2020).\n  - Regulation up averaged 404 MW (4% increase from 2020).\n\n- **Hourly Profile**: Regulation down requirements were generally higher than regulation up. Regulation up was highest during mid-day and early evening, while regulation down peaked from hours 8 to 21, especially when solar power was changing.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2021/page_185.jpg",
          "page_num": 185,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a1acf68b-2457-4d2c-8eec-30a7797bac68",
        "score": 0.4123754,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated May 2019. It includes Figure 6.4, which illustrates the quarterly average ancillary service requirements from 2016 to 2018. The services are categorized into regulation down, regulation up, spin, and non-spin, with their average requirements measured in megawatts (MW).\n\nThe text explains that since October 2016, the ISO has calculated regulation requirements based on observed needs from the previous year, updating values regularly. The ISO can also manually adjust requirements when necessary. In 2018, day-ahead requirements averaged 400 MW for regulation down and 320 MW for regulation up, marking a 14% increase for regulation down compared to 2017, with little change for regulation up. Real-time market requirements were similar to day-ahead market requirements.\n\nIn 2018, regulation requirements were set in increments of 50 MW, ranging from 300 MW to 650 MW. Regulation up requirements peaked during afternoon hours, while regulation down requirements were highest in the morning and evening, coinciding with solar ramping on and off. Regulation down requirements were generally higher than regulation up requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_157.jpg",
          "page_num": 157,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8ad24eee-183b-4e69-a4a2-d3881db1db1d",
        "score": 0.41008097,
        "text": "The document outlines the regulatory requirements and obligations for resource adequacy in the California ISO market. It details how the ISO collaborates with the CPUC and other authorities to set requirements for load-serving entities based on forecasted peak loads, including a planning reserve margin. Load-serving entities must demonstrate compliance through annual and monthly supply plans.\n\nFor annual showings, entities must prove they have procured 90% of their resource adequacy obligations for the summer months and 100% for monthly obligations. Plans are submitted to the ISO in advance of the compliance year or month.\n\nThe document also describes bidding and scheduling obligations. Scheduling coordinators must make resource adequacy capacity available in the ISO markets through:\n\n- **Day-ahead energy and ancillary services market**: All available capacity must be offered here.\n- **Residual unit commitment process**: Participants must submit bids priced at $0/MW.\n- **Real-time market**: Committed resources must be offered here, including short-start units.\n\nResource adequacy capacity not scheduled in the day-ahead market is not required in the real-time market unless specified. In 2018, half of the capacity was from resources that had to bid into the market each hour, except when unavailable due to outages.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_241.jpg",
          "page_num": 241,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "84bc55bc-69e7-475c-9438-c54feba6515c",
        "score": 0.402694,
        "text": "The document page from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated June 2018, includes a graph (Figure 6.5) showing the hourly average day-ahead regulation requirements for 2017. It compares the regulation down requirement and regulation up requirement in megawatts (MW) over a 24-hour period. The regulation down requirement peaks around 9-10 AM and again at 6 PM, while the regulation up requirement remains relatively stable.\n\nThe text discusses ancillary service procurement by fuel type from 2015 to 2017. It explains that ancillary service requirements are fulfilled by both internal resources and imports, with imports being limited by minimum procurement requirements. Ancillary services that bid across interties must compete for transmission capacity with energy. Most requirements are met by ISO resources, partly because scheduling coordinators are charged intertie congestion rates.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2017/page_157.jpg",
          "page_num": 157,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e1d44577-2ff8-4bb7-922f-5438367c5fdf",
        "score": 0.39244124,
        "text": "The document discusses the regulatory requirements and processes for resource adequacy in the California ISO market. It outlines how the ISO collaborates with the CPUC and local authorities to set system-level requirements for load-serving entities based on forecasted peak loads and a planning reserve margin, typically 15% of peak load. Entities must demonstrate compliance through annual and monthly supply plans.\n\nFor annual showings, entities must procure 90% of their obligations for the five summer months, and 100% for monthly obligations. Plans are submitted to the ISO by the end of October for the upcoming year, with monthly plans due 45 days before the compliance month.\n\nThe document also details bidding and scheduling obligations. All resource adequacy capacity must be bid into the day-ahead energy and ancillary services market or self-scheduled. The residual unit commitment process requires bids at $0/MW for all capacity. Real-time market commitments must also be offered, with specific rules for short-, medium-, and long-start units.\n\nIn 2019, 42% of the capacity was from resources not use-limited and bid into ISO markets continuously, primarily gas-fired resources. If no bids are submitted, the ISO automatically creates them.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2019/page_271.jpg",
          "page_num": 271,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": "2019",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "46e472c8-5563-451b-b55f-c1b2ca0c2dfe",
        "score": 0.38997492,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2022 Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring, California ISO, dated July 2023. It includes Figure 4.4, which illustrates the hourly average day-ahead regulation requirements for 2022, comparing regulation up and down for 2021 and 2022. The graph shows that regulation requirements fluctuate throughout the day, with peaks and troughs in demand.\n\nThe text discusses ancillary service procurement by fuel type from 2020 to 2022. It explains that ancillary service requirements are fulfilled by both internal resources and imports, with minimum procurement requirements set within the CAISO system. Ancillary services that bid across interties must compete for transmission capacity with energy. Most requirements are met by California ISO resources.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2022/page_159.jpg",
          "page_num": 159,
          "title": "2022 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4b2c284a-cf9a-4d57-a0af-d4fb20b8f0ca",
        "score": 0.38991728,
        "text": "The document is from the Department of Market Monitoring for the California ISO, dated August 2021. It discusses the first phase of a stakeholder process addressing three key areas: resource sufficiency, provision of transmission, and allocation of congestion rents. \n\n1. **Resource Sufficiency**: The extended day-ahead market design must allow entities to meet resource sufficiency obligations with power from resources scheduled over another balancing authority's transmission. Concerns are raised about the proposed firm transmission requirement, which could restrict transmission availability, affecting resource sufficiency.\n\n2. **Provision of Transmission**: The Western EIM is a voluntary market where transmission operators could offer unreserved transmission to the extended day-ahead market. While this could increase transmission availability, there are concerns about its impact on competitive access. The DMM suggests further consideration of mechanisms to ensure competitive access.\n\n3. **Congestion Revenues**: The allocation of congestion rents is crucial for incentivizing transmission provision. Allocating these rents to transmission owners could encourage them to make transmission available, but the allocation method needs careful consideration to ensure effectiveness.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2020/page_307.jpg",
          "page_num": 307,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2020,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "149f1944-041f-4b98-a5fc-6c4ae8990d6e",
        "score": 0.3846699,
        "text": "The document page discusses the average day-ahead regulation requirements by month since a methodology update on October 10, 2016, as reported by the Department of Market Monitoring for California ISO in June 2018. In 2017, the day-ahead requirements averaged around 320 MW for regulation up and 360 MW for regulation down, marking a decrease of about 22% for regulation up and 14% for regulation down compared to 2016. The real-time market requirements were similar to the day-ahead market in 2017.\n\nThe regulation requirements were typically set in increments of 50 MW between 300 MW and 500 MW. Regulation up requirements peaked during afternoon hours when solar power was decreasing, while regulation down requirements were higher in the late morning and evening when solar power was increasing or decreasing. Regulation down requirements were generally higher than regulation up, especially during midday, indicating a greater need for regulation down during the historical period used for calculations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2017/page_156.jpg",
          "page_num": 156,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7db8ebd3-aa51-4b3c-9977-19a7f394fdfe",
        "score": 0.3846153,
        "text": "The document discusses the resource adequacy program for the California ISO system, aimed at ensuring sufficient capacity for reliable grid operation. It involves collaboration with the California Energy Commission (CEC), California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC), and other local regulatory authorities to set procurement obligations for load-serving entities.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Purpose**: To ensure the grid has enough capacity to operate reliably, compensating fixed costs of existing generators through bilateral transactions.\n\n2. **Program Components**: \n   - System resource capacity for peak demand.\n   - Local resource capacity for specific areas with limited import capability.\n   - Flexible resource capacity for ramping periods.\n\n3. **Regulatory Requirements**: \n   - Load-serving entities must demonstrate procurement of adequate capacity.\n   - CPUC-jurisdictional entities must show 90% compliance for summer months and 100% for monthly obligations.\n   - The planning reserve margin (PRM) was set between 20-22.5% for 2022-2023.\n\nThe document also highlights the role of regulatory bodies in setting and enforcing these requirements to maintain grid reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2022/page_226.jpg",
          "page_num": 226,
          "title": "2022 Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4db53d55-755a-4f1f-90e4-3b50b8e466f2",
        "score": 0.38398942,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated August 2021. It discusses the requirements for load-serving entities to submit supply plans to the ISO, ensuring they meet their flexible resource adequacy obligations.\n\n### Bidding and Scheduling Obligations:\n- **All Resources**: Must submit economic energy and ancillary service bids in day-ahead and real-time markets.\n- **Category 1 (Base Flexibility)**: \n  - Must address both primary and secondary net load ramps.\n  - Submit bids for 17 hours daily, available 7 days a week.\n  - Covers 100% of the secondary net load ramp and part of the primary ramp.\n- **Category 2 (Peak Flexibility)**:\n  - Must address the primary net load ramp.\n  - Submit bids for 5 hours daily, available 7 days a week.\n  - Covers the difference between the maximum secondary and primary net load ramps.\n- **Category 3 (Super-Peak Flexibility)**:\n  - Must address the primary net load ramp.\n  - Submit bids for 5 hours on non-holiday weekdays.\n  - Set at 5% of the maximum three-hour net load ramp.\n\n### Requirements vs. Actual Maximum Net Load Ramps:\n- **Figure 9.5**: Compares resource adequacy requirements with actual net load ramps in 2020.\n- **Analysis**: Blue bars show total three-hour requirements, gold lines show maximum ramps, and green bars show requirements during maximum ramps.\n- **Variability**: Requirements differ daily and hourly due to different must-offer hours for each category.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of meeting flexible capacity requirements to ensure system reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2020/page_272.jpg",
          "page_num": 272,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2020,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

