        "text": "The document outlines the credit and training requirements for Congestion Revenue Rights (CRR) auctions and holdings, as well as the eligibility criteria for Load Serving Entities (LSEs) in CRR allocation.\n\n1. **Credit Requirements for CRR Auctions (3.2.1):** \n   - Candidates must provide security in line with ISO Tariff \u00a7 12 and the BPM for Credit Management to participate in CRR auctions.\n\n2. **Credit Requirements for Holding CRRs (3.2.2):**\n   - Market participants need sufficient collateral to hold CRRs, covering:\n     - Past and future trading days\n     - Completion of SRS trades\n     - Bidding in a CRR auction\n\n3. **Confirmation & Verification of LSE Status (3.3):**\n   - CRRs are allocated to LSEs serving local areas within the ISO Balancing Authority and to Qualified OBAALSEs.\n   - Entities must provide proof of their obligation to serve load, such as Settlement Quality Meter Data or documents filed with the California Energy Commission.\n\n4. **Training Requirements (3.4):**\n   - CRR Holders and Candidates must attend an ISO CRR training class before participating in CRR-related activities, unless waived by the ISO.\n   - They must employ or consult with someone who has attended the ISO\u2019s CRR training. Waivers are considered on a case-by-case basis.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Congestion_Revenue_Rights/page_22.jpg",
          "page_num": 22,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Congestion Revenue Rights",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a7979902-9091-4e5c-82ba-60c4f261666c",
        "score": 0.53300893,
        "text": "The document outlines the rules for Ancillary Services (AS) procurement. Key points include:\n\n- AS bids, unless self-provided, must be accompanied by an Energy Bid in the Day-Ahead Market (DAM) and Real-Time Market (RTM). These bids are part of the AS selection process, which includes energy and congestion market clearing.\n- An exception is made for capacity awarded regulation, where an Energy Bid is optional in RTM, except for MSS load-following resources.\n- If an AS Bid in DAM is included and does not cover the full capacity of the resource, the AS Bid uses available capacity not covered by the Energy Bid, with no opportunity cost in co-optimization.\n- An example is given with a resource having a maximum capacity of 100 MW, an Energy Bid of 90 MW, and an AS Bid of 20 MW. The system will co-optimize up to 90 MW, considering different combinations of energy and AS based on bid economics.\n- Any AS Bid beyond the Energy Bid Curve has zero opportunity cost, as illustrated in the example where the last 10 MW of AS bid incurs no opportunity cost.\n- A non-zero opportunity cost for an Energy Bid occurs only if the total resource capacity is allocated between Energy and Ancillary Services, as shown in a scenario with 80 MW of Energy and 20 MW of spin awarded.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_195.jpg",
          "page_num": 195,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a7e30d27-a1f7-4382-b0e6-6f189ce477a4",
        "score": 0.5318886,
        "text": "The document page outlines components related to bidding in ancillary services, specifically focusing on Regulation Ramp Rate, Energy Limit Bid, and Distribution Curve Bid.\n\n1. **Regulation Ramp Rate**: \n   - Required for bids involving Regulation Up or Down.\n   - Represents the ramp rate of a resource for procurement and dispatch.\n   - Must match the maximum rate registered in the Master File if subject to CAISO Tariff Appendix II.\n   - Constant across the Trading Day.\n\n2. **Energy Limit Bid Component**:\n   - Not required for resources without energy limits.\n   - Applies to Use-Limited Resources, which have constraints due to factors like hydro conditions or regulatory considerations.\n   - Includes maximum and minimum daily energy limits (MWh), with specific values for generation and pumping modes.\n   - Fixed for the entire Trading Day and submitted only in the Day-Ahead Market (DAM).\n\n3. **Distribution Curve Bid Component**:\n   - Pertains to resources in various physical and proxy demand response settings.\n   - Includes the Distribution Location, defined by the Connectivity Node (CNode) associated with the resource.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of these components in the bidding process and their specific requirements.",
