        "text": "The document page discusses configurations and limitations for multi-stage generators (MSG) and conditionally available resources within the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) framework.\n\n1. **Configurations and Limitations**:\n   - The table shows three configurations (CONFIG_1, CONFIG_2, CONFIG_3) that are offline, with CAISO deriving values of 0 for each.\n   - The document explains that the same implied start restrictions (IMPLIED_STRTRS) apply to both PLANT_C and CONFIG_A. These should be registered under specific limitations in the ULPDT (USE_LIMIT_TYPE='START').\n   - PLANT_C limitations are registered without a configuration ID, while CONFIG_A limitations are registered under configuration 3.\n   - The GRDT MSG_CONFIG tab will register these as CONFIG_1=1, CONFIG_2=2, and CONFIG_3=3, with CAISO deriving transitions.\n\n2. **Multi-Stage Generator with Registered Run Hour Limitation**:\n   - MSG resources can have run hour limitations at the plant or configuration level, considered in the opportunity cost calculator.\n   - CAISO enforces run hour limitations through the bid-in Daily Energy Limit at the MSG plant level, not at the configuration level.\n\n3. **Conditionally Available Resource (CAR)**:\n   - A Scheduling Coordinator can register a resource as a CAR if it has operational or regulatory limits causing frequent unavailability, but not qualifying as a Use-Limited Resource.\n   - A resource can be both a Use-Limited Resource and a CAR, allowing dual registration.\n   - Examples include regulatory noise limitations and hybrid technologies like wind or solar with battery components.",
